24
00:01:08,020 --> 00:01:11,020
 So, I came to databases late in life.

25
00:01:11,020 --> 00:01:14,360
 I saw them a little bit in grad school,

26
00:01:14,360 --> 00:01:15,500
 which was a very long time ago,

27
00:01:15,500 --> 00:01:17,920
 and I didn't like relational database as much,

28
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:22,680
 and I went to a job, and I had learned relational databases

29
00:01:22,680 --> 00:01:26,920
 for the job, and I actually was a pretty advanced programmer

30
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:30,440
 at that point in time, and so they taught me

31
00:01:30,440 --> 00:01:33,600
 how to do data model design, and I picked it up really fast,

32
00:01:33,600 --> 00:01:36,560
 and I like totally fell in love with databases.

33
00:01:36,560 --> 00:01:41,100
 So, model design is a interesting problem to solve.

34
00:01:41,100 --> 00:01:44,660
 The basic idea really comes down to efficiency

35
00:01:44,660 --> 00:01:46,800
 of storing and retrieving data.

36
00:01:46,800 --> 00:01:48,280
 And it just comes down to like,

37
00:01:48,280 --> 00:01:51,800
 if you build an online application like Facebook,

38
00:01:51,800 --> 00:01:54,020
 and if you're not clever about how to store your data,

39
00:01:54,020 --> 00:01:56,000
 and somehow every time you logged into Facebook,

40
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,420
 you had to read all the Facebook's data to finally log in,

41
00:01:59,420 --> 00:02:03,420
 it would literally take you two to 3,000 hours

42
00:02:03,420 --> 00:02:06,640
 to log into Facebook if it had to read all of its data.

43
00:02:06,640 --> 00:02:08,600
 Now, obviously, millions of people

44
00:02:08,600 --> 00:02:10,840
 log in per second in Facebook,

45
00:02:10,840 --> 00:02:12,680
 and so obviously they're a little faster than that.

46
00:02:12,680 --> 00:02:15,040
 So, somewhere between days and days and days

47
00:02:15,040 --> 00:02:17,540
 to read the data, and can read the data

48
00:02:17,540 --> 00:02:19,160
 a million times a second,

49
00:02:19,160 --> 00:02:20,920
 in there is where databases win.

50
00:02:20,920 --> 00:02:24,040
 And so, at times, it seems like when we're building

51
00:02:24,040 --> 00:02:26,160
 a data model, you're like, "Oh, this is so difficult,

52
00:02:26,160 --> 00:02:28,160
 "why are we working so hard?"

53
00:02:28,160 --> 00:02:30,920
 And the answer is, you just can't scale.

54
00:02:30,920 --> 00:02:32,560
 I mean, you can read through your data

55
00:02:32,560 --> 00:02:33,960
 for simple data mining things,

56
00:02:33,960 --> 00:02:35,560
 but databases are really important,

57
00:02:35,560 --> 00:02:36,660
 and especially when you're building

58
00:02:36,660 --> 00:02:39,200
 interactive online applications, speed's important.

59
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:43,560
 So, it turns out that, like most things in database,

60
00:02:43,560 --> 00:02:45,340
 you can learn the basics pretty quick,

61
00:02:45,340 --> 00:02:46,880
 and the rest of it is sort of an art form

62
00:02:46,880 --> 00:02:49,520
 that you learn as you go.

63
00:02:49,520 --> 00:02:52,520
 And so, the goal is to figure out the data

64
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:54,640
 that you want to store in your application,

65
00:02:54,640 --> 00:02:56,640
 and then draw a picture,

66
00:02:56,640 --> 00:02:58,980
 spreading that data across multiple tables,

67
00:02:58,980 --> 00:03:01,560
 and then creating links between those tables.

68
00:03:01,560 --> 00:03:03,840
 So, you kind of start with a sample data set.

69
00:03:03,840 --> 00:03:05,240
 Now, this is where we're gonna end up,

70
00:03:05,240 --> 00:03:07,660
 and this is the model for the data

71
00:03:07,660 --> 00:03:10,040
 for this local library application that we're building,

72
00:03:10,040 --> 00:03:12,480
 and this is the thing we're gonna keep coming back to

73
00:03:12,480 --> 00:03:13,320
 over and over.

74
00:03:13,320 --> 00:03:15,380
 So, this is the destination,

75
00:03:15,380 --> 00:03:17,200
 but we're not gonna hit this destination,

76
00:03:17,200 --> 00:03:19,520
 we're gonna start more with the data.

77
00:03:19,520 --> 00:03:20,920
 Now, different applications,

78
00:03:20,920 --> 00:03:22,600
 when you work at different organizations,

79
00:03:22,600 --> 00:03:26,080
 you're going to find that the data model is very important.

80
00:03:26,080 --> 00:03:28,040
 So, this is the data model of my autograder,

81
00:03:28,040 --> 00:03:30,840
 which is based on a framework I built called SUGI,

82
00:03:30,840 --> 00:03:34,060
 and so, if you were to learn this thing,

83
00:03:34,060 --> 00:03:36,020
 early on I say, oh, and here's our data model,

84
00:03:36,020 --> 00:03:37,080
 and here's how we store stuff,

85
00:03:37,080 --> 00:03:38,480
 and here's this, that, and the other thing,

86
00:03:38,480 --> 00:03:41,760
 and this data model took a lot of time to get right,

87
00:03:41,760 --> 00:03:45,520
 and it's a real important part of the application.

88
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:47,680
 And another project I work on is called Sakai,

89
00:03:47,680 --> 00:03:50,240
 it's a learning management system that's open source.

90
00:03:50,240 --> 00:03:53,080
 And, you know, this is a tiny fraction of the data model,

91
00:03:53,080 --> 00:03:54,760
 but if you wanna work in this application,

92
00:03:54,760 --> 00:03:57,200
 you wanna improve something or add a feature,

93
00:03:57,200 --> 00:03:58,640
 you gotta figure out this data model,

94
00:03:58,640 --> 00:04:00,840
 because where the data goes,

95
00:04:00,840 --> 00:04:03,560
 it shows up kind of flat in the user interface,

96
00:04:03,560 --> 00:04:06,760
 but eventually it's stored in very specific locations,

97
00:04:06,760 --> 00:04:08,740
 and linked, and that's why you see all these little boxes,

98
00:04:08,740 --> 00:04:09,580
 but then lines.

99
00:04:09,580 --> 00:04:12,960
 The lines are also the links between the various tables.

100
00:04:12,960 --> 00:04:15,380
 So, there's a whole bunch of theory

101
00:04:15,380 --> 00:04:18,140
 about database normalization, and it's important,

102
00:04:18,140 --> 00:04:20,040
 it really is, and if you take some time,

103
00:04:20,040 --> 00:04:22,240
 go ahead and read about it.

104
00:04:22,240 --> 00:04:24,960
 First normal form, second normal form, third normal form,

105
00:04:24,960 --> 00:04:27,640
 third normal form, version A and stuff.

106
00:04:27,640 --> 00:04:28,900
 I'm not really into the math,

107
00:04:28,900 --> 00:04:32,000
 I don't really wanna explain the math to you.

108
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:36,380
 The key thing about database normalization, ultimately,

109
00:04:36,380 --> 00:04:40,620
 that it can be sort of distilled down to,

110
00:04:40,620 --> 00:04:43,000
 don't replicate string data,

111
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:44,920
 and what I mean by string data is like,

112
00:04:44,920 --> 00:04:48,180
 names, and URLs, and things like that.

113
00:04:49,520 --> 00:04:51,520
 So, in a system, ultimately,

114
00:04:51,520 --> 00:04:56,440
 if my email address is stored in text in that system,

115
00:04:56,440 --> 00:04:58,140
 it literally should be stored once.

116
00:04:58,140 --> 00:05:00,200
 There should be no email address,

117
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:01,440
 email address, email address.

118
00:05:01,440 --> 00:05:04,000
 What you need is to have the email address one place,

119
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:06,040
 and then kind of give that email address a number,

120
00:05:06,040 --> 00:05:08,320
 and all the places you wanna indicate

121
00:05:08,320 --> 00:05:10,280
 about that email address you used the number in.

122
00:05:10,280 --> 00:05:12,840
 So, these integer numbers are the key.

123
00:05:12,840 --> 00:05:16,400
 So, we create keys, which are the lookup handles,

124
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:18,000
 and then we point to those keys,

125
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:20,300
 and we use integers to make links between the tables,

126
00:05:20,300 --> 00:05:22,720
 'cause integers are fast,

127
00:05:22,720 --> 00:05:24,540
 they're the thing that computers understand better.

128
00:05:24,540 --> 00:05:26,680
 They understand, computers understand

129
00:05:26,680 --> 00:05:28,400
 and move integers around.

130
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:30,400
 They use less data, they calculate,

131
00:05:30,400 --> 00:05:32,020
 they compare really fast,

132
00:05:32,020 --> 00:05:34,420
 and so it's very, integers are very important.

133
00:05:34,420 --> 00:05:39,240
 So, up next, we're gonna take a look at some example data,

134
